            <ul class="bullets">
              <li><strong>Misogyny:</strong> systemic violence against women.</li>
              <li><strong>Body Politics:</strong> reclaiming the female body from objectification.</li>
              <li><strong>Emotional Labour:</strong> unpaid, invisible work in relationships.</li>
              <li><strong>Intersectionality:</strong> race, gender, and trauma intertwined.</li>
            </ul>
          </article>
          <article class="content-card">
            <div class="card-tag">Influences</div>
            <ul class="bullets">
              <li><strong>bell hooks:</strong> intersectional feminism &amp; love as politics.</li>
              <li><strong>Audre Lorde:</strong> poetry as self-definition &amp; power.</li>
              <li><strong>Adrienne Rich:</strong> validating women’s lived experiences.</li>
            </ul>
            <button class="btn btn-outline" data-open-modal="instapoetry">
              <span class="icon">★</span>
              <span>Instapoetry Revolution</span>
            </button>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SLIDE 7: RESEARCH GAP -->
    <section id="slide-7" class="slide">
      <div class="slide-inner animate-in">
        <h2 class="section-title">Research Gap</h2>
        <p class="subtitle">Why This Study is Needed</p>

        <div class="grid-2">
          <article class="content-card">
            <div class="card-tag">Gap</div>
            <h3>Limited Psychoanalytic Examination</h3>
            <p>
              Despite global popularity, <em>Milk and Honey</em> rarely receives rigorous
              psychoanalytic readings, especially through Freud, Lacan, or Kristeva.
            </p>
            <div class="pill"><span></span> Opportunity for deeper theory</div>
          </article>
          <article class="content-card">
            <div class="card-tag">Gap</div>
            <h3>Minimal Trauma Theory Application</h3>
            <p>
              The collection is central to trauma discourse but seldom analysed using
              formal trauma theory frameworks.
            </p>
            <div class="pill"><span></span> Interdisciplinary potential</div>
          </article>
          <article class="content-card">
            <div class="card-tag">Gap</div>
            <h3>Neglect of Cultural Impact</h3>
            <p>
              The Instapoetry boom is often dismissed as “less literary”, leaving its
              cultural labour under-theorised.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="content-card">
            <div class="card-tag">Gap</div>
            <h3>Absence of Intersecting Frameworks</h3>
            <p>
              Very few studies weave together trauma, psychoanalysis, and feminist
              theory in reading Kaur’s work.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SLIDE 8: RESEARCH OBJECTIVES -->
    <section id="slide-8" class="slide">
      <div class="slide-inner animate-in">
        <h2 class="section-title">Research Objectives</h2>
        <p class="subtitle">What This Study Seeks to Do</p>

        <div class="grid-3">
          <article class="content-card">
            <div class="card-tag">01</div>
            <h3>Analyse Trauma &amp; Memory</h3>
            <p>
              Explore how Kaur represents repression and unconscious memory
              through symbolic, minimalist language.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="content-card">
            <div class="card-tag">02</div>
            <h3>Study Poetic Fragmentation</h3>
            <p>
              Examine how the structure of <em>Milk and Honey</em> mirrors the disrupted,
              non-linear logic of trauma.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="content-card">
            <div class="card-tag">03</div>
            <h3>Examine Healing &amp; Reconstruction</h3>
            <p>
              Trace processes of recovery, self-reclamation, and identity rebuilding
              across the four sections.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="content-card">
            <div class="card-tag">04</div>
            <h3>Apply Psychoanalytic Theories</h3>
            <p>
              Mobilise Freud, Lacan, and Kristeva to read imagery, voice, and
              narrative gaps.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="content-card">
            <div class="card-tag">05</div>
            <h3>Situate Within Feminist Trauma Writing</h3>
            <p>
              Position the collection within broader feminist literature on gendered
              violence and empowerment.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SLIDE 9: METHODOLOGY -->
    <section id="slide-9" class="slide">
      <div class="slide-inner animate-in">
        <h2 class="section-title">Methodology</h2>
        <p class="subtitle">Qualitative Textual Analysis</p>

        <div class="grid-2">
          <article class="content-card">
            <div class="card-tag">Design</div>
            <h3>Research Design &amp; Primary Text</h3>
            <ul class="bullets">
              <li>Close reading of selected poems from <em>Milk and Honey</em>.</li>
              <li>Attention to imagery, metaphor, structure, and silence.</li>
              <li>Poems chosen from all four sections to track transformation.</li>
            </ul>
          </article>
          <article class="content-card">
            <div class="card-tag">Sources</div>
            <h3>Secondary Sources &amp; Frameworks</h3>
            <ul class="bullets">
              <li>Trauma theory (Caruth, Herman).</li>
              <li>Psychoanalysis (Freud, Lacan, Kristeva).</li>
              <li>Feminist criticism and Instapoetry scholarship.</li>
            </ul>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SLIDE 10: TIMELINE -->
    <section id="slide-10" class="slide">
